
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `espdiff` baraye moghayese kardan file-haye ESP (Electronic System Protection) estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad ta tafavot-ha ra dar configuration-ha ya dastoorat be kar rafte dar system-haye ESP peyda konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `espdiff file1 file2` --> 📂 Moghayese do file ESP va namayesh tafavot-ha.
    🔹 `espdiff -i file1 file2` --> 👓 Ignore kardan fargh-haye case (bozorgi va kuchiki horoof) dar moghayese.
    🔹 `espdiff -w file1 file2` --> 🗑 Ignore kardan space-haye zaed (whitespace) dar moghayese.
    🔹 `espdiff -s file1 file2` --> 🤫 Namayesh faghat resume moghayese bedune etela’at tafsili.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ espdiff config1.esp config2.esp

    🔹 Moghayese file-haye `config1.esp` va `config2.esp` va namayesh tafavot-ha.

    $ espdiff -i settings.esp new_settings.esp

    🔹 Moghayese `settings.esp` va `new_settings.esp` ba ignore kardan fargh-haye case.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ espdiff -s old.esp current.esp

    🔹 Namayesh faghat resume moghayese file-haye `old.esp` va `current.esp`, baraye didan chand ta fargh asasi vojood dare.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `espdiff` command is used to compare ESP (Electronic System Protection) files. This command helps you find differences in configurations or commands used in ESP systems.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `espdiff file1 file2` --> 📂 Compare two ESP files and display the differences.
    🔹 `espdiff -i file1 file2` --> 👓 Ignore case differences during comparison.
    🔹 `espdiff -w file1 file2` --> 🗑 Ignore whitespace differences during comparison.
    🔹 `espdiff -s file1 file2` --> 🤫 Show only the summary of the comparison without detailed information.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ espdiff config1.esp config2.esp

    🔹 Compare the files `config1.esp` and `config2.esp` and display the differences.

    $ espdiff -i settings.esp new_settings.esp

    🔹 Compare `settings.esp` and `new_settings.esp` ignoring case differences.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ espdiff -s old.esp current.esp

    🔹 Display only the summary of the comparison between `old.esp` and `current.esp` files, to quickly see how many significant differences exist.

